🏷️ What are Annotations in Spring?
👉 Annotations are special markers (metadata) you put on classes/methods to tell Spring what to do

🧠 In Simple Words
“Annotations = instructions for Spring”

Instead of writing long XML configs ❌
You just write:
@Service

👉 And Spring understands:
“Oh, I need to create and manage this class as a bean”

🔥 Why Annotations Exist

Before annotations:
- Lots of XML 😵
- Hard to read
- Hard to maintain

After annotations:
- Clean code ✅
- Easy setup ✅
- Faster development ✅

🚀 Most Important Spring Annotations

🫘 1. @Component
👉 Basic annotation to create a bean

@Component
public class MyClass {}

👉 Spring will:
- Detect it
- Create object
- Manage it

🧩 2. @Service
@Service
public class UserService {}

👉 Same as @Component, but used for:
Business logic layer

🗄️ 3. @Repository
@Repository
public class UserRepository {}

👉 Used for:
- Database layer
- JPA repositories

🌐 4. @Controller / @RestController
@RestController
public class UserController {}

👉 Used for:
- Handling HTTP requests
- Building APIs


👉 These are all special types of @Component
| Annotation  | Purpose        |
| ----------- | -------------- |
| @Component  | General        |
| @Service    | Business logic |
| @Repository | DB layer       |
| @Controller | Web layer      |


💉 5. @Autowired
@Autowired
private UserService userService;

👉 Tells Spring:
“Inject this dependency automatically”

⚙️ 6. @Configuration
@Configuration
public class AppConfig {}

👉 Used to define:
Manual beans (@Bean)

🏭 7. @Bean
@Bean
public NotificationService notificationService() {
    return new NotificationService();
}

👉 Manually creates a bean


Lifecycle of bean:

🟢 1. Bean Creation
Spring creates object:

new LifecycleBean(...)

👉 Constructor is called
Constructor Called

💉 2. Dependency Injection
Spring injects dependencies:

NotificationService → injected

👉 Your object now has everything it needs

⚙️ 3. Initialization Phase
Spring calls init method:

init()

👉 Because you wrote:

@Bean(initMethod = "init")
Bean initialized


✅ 4. Bean Ready (Usage Phase)
Now bean is ready:

lifecycleBean.performTask();
Ready for use!

👉 This is where your app actually uses the bean


🔴 5. Destruction Phase
When app shuts down:

context.close();

Spring calls:
cleanup()
cleanup() being called

🎯 Full Flow (One View)
1. Create Bean → Constructor
2. Inject Dependencies
3. Call init()
4. Bean Ready (Use it)
5. Call destroy() on shutdown
